621
00:53:46,882 --> 00:53:50,767
25136, Resolution to Update Inclusionary Zoning for Fractional Affordable Housing Incentives.

622
00:53:50,807 --> 00:54:02,280
This is an update from a paper that we approved in December, which referred the affordable housing fractional incentive to the Affordable Housing Trust Fund Board for specific recommendations.

623
00:54:03,141 --> 00:54:04,703
And we do have that back.

624
00:54:05,443 --> 00:54:07,245
from the affordable housing trust fund board.

625
00:54:07,285 --> 00:54:09,728
We have our housing planner Catherine Buckingham here with us.

626
00:54:10,329 --> 00:54:14,855
We have a letter from I think we have Lisa Ann Davidson, the chair of the affordable housing trust on Zoom as well.

627
00:54:15,415 --> 00:54:24,427
We did receive a letter back, dear city councilors, on behalf of the Medford affordable housing trust fund board, I'm ready to express enthusiastic support for an ordinance that would allow the city of Medford to accept fractional payments

628
00:54:24,867 --> 00:54:27,708
to be paid in lieu of rounding up the number of affordable units created.

629
00:54:28,128 --> 00:54:37,430
This past fall, Councilor Lemming presented Resolution 25136 to the Board supporting a fractional payment ordinance and calling on the Affordable Housing Trust Fund Board to make recommendations on how to update this policy.

630
00:54:37,891 --> 00:54:43,292
In subsequent months, the Board was given frequent updates from city staff members and provided feedback regarding specific language for this ordinance.

631
00:54:43,812 --> 00:54:46,773
The Board unanimously voted to voice our approval of this ordinance as included below.

632
00:54:47,233 --> 00:54:54,075
This change has a potential to increase the amount of housing constructed by reducing the incentive for developers to limit the size of their developments in order to avoid rounding up.

633
00:54:54,495 --> 00:54:56,396
the number of affordable units they're required to provide.

634
00:54:56,476 --> 00:55:03,721
Furthermore, the revenue from fractional payments will be a valuable funding source to the Affordable Housing Trust Fund, allowing future investment in supporting affordable housing in Medford.

635
00:55:04,161 --> 00:55:11,746
We respectfully request and encourage members of the City Council to support this important initiative, and thank you for your steadfast commitment to enhancing affordable housing opportunities in Medford.

636
00:55:11,786 --> 00:55:15,609
Sincerely, Lisa Davidson, Chair of the Medford Affordable Housing Trust Fund Board.

637
00:55:16,229 --> 00:55:19,051
And the ordinance here is Fractional Payments Suggested Language.

638
00:55:20,372 --> 00:55:20,692
You know what?

639
00:55:20,952 --> 00:55:23,834
I'll let you handle it, Catherine, but I'll go to Matt first.

640
00:55:26,265 --> 00:55:35,356
Thank you, and thank you, Catherine, for coming out here, and Lisa as well on Zoom for coming out here to present this to us.

641
00:55:36,217 --> 00:55:41,684
Very pleased to see that the Affordable Housing Trust got back with recommended language on

642
00:55:43,666 --> 00:55:46,928
on for fractional payments.

643
00:55:47,368 --> 00:55:54,752
Just so that folks sort of understand what this is from a more layman's perspective, I'm just going to try to explain the math behind what's going on here.

644
00:55:59,474 --> 00:56:07,837
Under Medford's current ordinances, you can build nine units by right and none of them have to be affordable.

645
00:56:07,938 --> 00:56:13,640
They don't have to be affordable under the MGL definition of affordability.

646
00:56:14,258 --> 00:56:21,202
when you get to 10 units, when you get to that threshold, 10% of units have to be affordable.

647
00:56:21,823 --> 00:56:24,444
So if you build 10 units, then one of them has to be affordable.

648
00:56:24,885 --> 00:56:40,294
The issue with that is that after 10 units, like between I believe 10 and 20, 10% of however many units you're building have to be affordable, and the issue with that is that if that becomes a fraction, then you have to round up.

649
00:56:40,934 --> 00:56:42,215
So if you wanna build 11 units,

650
00:56:44,467 --> 00:56:48,908
Then that means then 10 percent of 11 is 1.1 and you round up to 2.

651
00:56:50,269 --> 00:56:56,831
So that means that essentially what this means is that we have a lot of nine unit buildings in Medford.

652
00:56:57,511 --> 00:57:08,254
And if you start and people are strongly disincentivized from building certain levels of units like certain numbers of units because you know you

653
00:57:08,968 --> 00:57:15,150
really don't want to build an 11-unit property because then you're required to make two of those affordable from 11 until, I believe, 20.

654
00:57:15,270 --> 00:57:24,934
What the fractional payment does is it means that if you want to build 11 units, then you don't have to build two affordable units.

655
00:57:24,954 --> 00:57:27,074
You have to build one affordable unit, then you can take that 0.1

656
00:57:29,901 --> 00:57:41,528
in fraction, like fraction of a unit, take the equivalent amount that that would cost and then put it into the Affordable Housing Trust instead of building an additional affordable unit.

657
00:57:41,648 --> 00:57:57,997
What this does, in effect, is it allows us to get more units built and more money into the Affordable Housing Trust, which is, I'm sure, a goal that everybody can agree advances the goals of affordable housing.

658
00:57:59,458 --> 00:58:03,820
different ways that municipalities have implemented these fractional incentives.

659
00:58:04,461 --> 00:58:10,383
And I'm glad to hear that the Affordable Housing Trust has given us a proposal for how to do that.

